org.apache.juneau.http

Class StringRange

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.apache.juneau.http.StringRange
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Comparable<StringRange>

    @BeanIgnore
public final class StringRange
extends Object
implements Comparable<StringRange>
    Represents a single value in a comma-delimited header value that optionally contains a quality metric for comparison and extension parameters.

    Similar in concept to MediaTypeRange except instead of media types (e.g. "text/json"), it's a simple type (e.g. "iso-8601").

    An example of a type range is a value in an Accept-Encoding header.

    See Also:
    • Hypertext Transfer Protocol -- HTTP/1.1

    • Method Detail

      • parse

        public static StringRange[] parse(String value)
        Parses a header such as an Accept-Encoding header value into an array of type ranges.

        The syntax expected to be found in the referenced value complies with the syntax described in RFC2616, Section 14.1, as described below:

        Accept-Encoding = "Accept-Encoding" ":" 1#( codings [ ";" "q" "=" qvalue ] ) codings = ( content-coding | "*" )

        Examples of its use are:

        Accept-Encoding: compress, gzip Accept-Encoding: Accept-Encoding: * Accept-Encoding: compress;q=0.5, gzip;q=1.0 Accept-Encoding: gzip;q=1.0, identity; q=0.5, *;q=0

        Parameters:
        value - The value to parse. If null or empty, returns a single TypeRange is returned that represents all types.
        Returns:
        The type ranges described by the string.
        The ranges are sorted such that the most acceptable type is available at ordinal position '0', and the least acceptable at position n-1.

      • getQValue

        public Float getQValue()
        Returns the 'q' (quality) value for this type, as described in Section 3.9 of RFC2616.

        The quality value is a float between 0.0 (unacceptable) and 1.0 (most acceptable).

        If 'q' value doesn't make sense for the context (e.g. this range was extracted from a "content-*" header, as opposed to "accept-*" header, its value will always be "1".

        Returns:
        The 'q' value for this type, never null.

      • compareTo

        public int compareTo(StringRange o)
        Compares two MediaRanges for equality.

        The values are first compared according to qValue values. Should those values be equal, the type is then lexicographically compared (case-insensitive) in ascending order, with the "*" type demoted last in that order. TypeRanges with the same types but with extensions are promoted over those same types with no extensions.

        Specified by:
        compareTo in interface Comparable<StringRange>
        Parameters:
        o - The range to compare to. Never null.

      • matches

        public boolean matches(String type)
        Checks if the specified type matches this range.

        The type will match this range if the range type string is the same or "*".

        Parameters:
        type - The type to match against this range.
        Returns:
        true if the specified type matches this range.
